{"title_page": "List of English words of Dravidian origin", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a list of [[English language|English]] words that are [[Loanword|borrowed]] directly or ultimately from [[Dravidian languages]]. Dravidian languages include [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Kannada language|Kannada]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], and a number of other languages spoken mainly in [[South Asia]]. The list is by no means exhaustive.\n\nSome of the words can be traced to specific languages, but others have disputed or uncertain origins. Words of disputed or less certain origin are in the \"Dravidian languages\" list. Where [[lexicographer]]s generally agree on a source language, the words are listed by language.\n\n==Dravidian languages==\n*[[wikt:aiyo|Aiyo]], a word used to express distress, regret and fear, either from Tamil ''aiy\u014d'' or [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] ayiy\u014d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/aiyo|title=aiyo|website=Oxford Dictionaries - English}}</ref>\n*[[Betel]], a leaf of a vine belonging to the family Piperaceae; from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''betel'', which probably comes from Tamil or Malayalam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=betel|title=Betel |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>\n*[[Candy]], crystallized sugar or confection made from sugar; via Persian ''qand'', which is probably from a Dravidian language, ultimately stemming from the Sanskrit root word 'Khanda'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=candy&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Candy |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n* [[Coir]], cord/rope, fibre from husk of coconut; from Malayalam ''kayar'' (\u0d15\u0d2f\u0d7c)<ref name=\"Coir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=coir|title=Coir |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> or Tamil ''kayiru'' (\u0b95\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0bc1).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/coir |title=Coir |publisher=Dictionary.com |accessdate=2015-07-26}}</ref> The origin of this word cannot be conclusively attributed to Malayalam or Tamil.\n*[[Congee]], porridge, water with rice; uncertain origin, possibly from Tamil ''kanji'' (\u0b95\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/congee |title=Congee |publisher=Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary |date=2012-08-31 |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref> Telugu or Kannada ''ga\u00f1ji'', or Malayalam ''ka\u1e47ni''<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=conjee, congee ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref>\n*[[Coolie]], a labourer or slave, a South Asian person; possibly from Tamil ''cooli'' (\u0b95\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bbf) \"labour\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/coolie|title=Coolie; Define Coolie at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> or possibly from ''Ko\u1e37\u012b'' \"[[Gujarati people]]\" in [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=coolie ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> which is not a Dravidian language\n*[[Bed frame|Cot]], a bedstead or a portable bed; via [[Hindi]] from [[Sanskrit]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=cot ''n.<sup>4</sup>''|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref> which in turn may have come from a Dravidian source such as Tamil ''kattil''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cot&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Cowry]], the shells of certain sea snails, or the snails themselves; via Hindi and [[Urdu]] from Sanskrit ''kaparda'' (\u0915\u092a\u0930\u094d\u0926),<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=cowry ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref> which may be related to Tamil ''kotu'' (\u0b95\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bc1) \"shell\"<ref name=\"etymonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cowrie&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Curry]], a variety of dishes flavored with a spicy sauce; [[cognate]]s exist in several Dravidian languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/curry|title=Curry; Define Curry at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n*[[Ginger]], a fragrant spice; exact route from Dravidian is uncertain, but possibly from Tamil ''inchi'' (\u0b87\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf) or Malayalam ''inchi'' (\u0d07\u0d1e\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d3f)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RSGOJB2lwmUC&pg|title=Origins of Plant Names-D.A. Patil}}</ref>\n* [[Godown]], synonym to warehouse; English from Malay, which in turn may have borrowed it from Telugu ''gi\u1e0dangi'' or Tamil ''ki\u1e6danku''<ref>{{Cite web|title=Define Godown at Dictionary.com|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/godown|accessdate=January 4, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Gunny sack|Gunny]], an inexpensive bag; from Sanskrit via Hindi and [[Marathi language|Marathi]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=gunny, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2000 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> perhaps ultimately from a Dravidian language such as [[Tulu language|Tulu]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n*[[Hot toddy]], beverage made of alcoholic liquor with hot water, sugar, and spices; from Hindi ''tari'' \"palm sap\", probably from a Dravidian language<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=toddy |title=toddy |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n*[[Jaggery]], coarse brown sugar made from palm and sugarcane; via Portuguese j\u00e1gara<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/jaggery|title=Jaggery|publisher=Merriam Webster Dictionary}}</ref> probably from Malayalam ''chakkara'' (\u0d1a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d30)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memidex.com/jaggery|title=Jaggery Etymology}}</ref> or Kannada ''sakkare'',  having its origins in Sanskrit.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=jaggery, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref>\n*[[Mango]], A tropical fruit;origin probably from Malayalam<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mango|title=Mango; Define Mango at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mango|title=Mango |website=Merriam-Webster.com}}</ref> or Tamil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=mango |title=mango (n.) |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>Achaya, K.T. (2003). The Story of Our Food. Universities Press. p. 7. {{ISBN|9788173712937}}.</ref>\n*[[Mongoose]], a small carnivorous mammal from southern Eurasia or Africa, known for killing snakes; probably ultimately from a Dravidian language, with spelling influenced by the English word ''goose''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=mongoose |title=mongoose |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n*[[Mung bean|Mung]], a type of bean; ultimately from Sanskrit ''mudga'' (\u092e\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0917), which is the name of the bean and the plant, perhaps via Tamil ''m\u016bngu'' (\u0bae\u0bc1\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1) \"soak\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mung+bean |title=Mung bean &#124; Define Mung bean at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> or perhaps from ''m\u0169g'' (\u092e\u0942\u0901\u0917), the name of the bean in Hindi,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=mung ''n.<sup>2</sup>''|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> which is not a Dravidian language\n*[[Orange (word)|Orange]], a citrus fruit, or a color named for the fruit; cognates exist in several Dravidian languages<ref name=OED>{{cite encyclopedia | year = 2013 | title = orange ''n''.<sup>1</sup> and ''adj''.<sup>1</sup> | encyclopedia = Oxford English Dictionary online | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | url =http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/132163 |accessdate=2013-09-30}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n*[[Pagoda]], a religious building; etymology uncertain but perhaps influenced by Tamil ''pagavadi'' (\u0baa\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0b9f\u0bbf) \"house belonging to a deity\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=pagoda&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*Pariah, a social outcast; from Tamil ''pa\u1e5faiyar'' (\u0baa\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bb0\u0bcd) or Malayalam ''pa\u1e5fayan'', \"drummer\"<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=pariah, ''n''. and ''adj''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref>\n*[[Peacock]], a type of bird; from [[Old English]] ''pawa'', the earlier etymology is uncertain, but one possible source is Tamil ''tokei'' (\u0ba4\u0bcb\u0b95\u0bc8) \"peacock feather\", via [[Latin]] or [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=peacock&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Sambal]], a spicy condiment; from [[Malay language|Malay]], which may have borrowed the word from a Dravidian language such as Tamil or Telugu<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/sambal|title=Sambal; Define Sambal at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n*[[Teak]], a tropical hardwood tree; called ''tekku'' (\u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1) in Tamil, ''tekka'' in Malayalam,  Telugu ''teku'', and Kannada ''tegu''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=teak |title=teak |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Malayalam==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Word||Transliteration||Meaning in Malayalam\n|-\n|[[Areca]]||\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15||adekka||areca nut <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/areca|title=Areca |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Catechu]]||\u0d15\u0d36\u0d42||cashoo||astringent made from acacia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/catechu|title=Catechu |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordreference.com/definition/catechu|title=Catechu |website=WordReference.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Copra]]||\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d30||kopra||copra: kernel of coconut <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=copra&searchmode=none |title=Copra |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Calico]]||\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d34\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d||k\u0113\u0101\u1e3bikk\u0113\u0101\u1e6d||name of the place it originates from (Calicut) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/calico|title=Calico |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jackfruit]]||\u0d1a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15||Chakka||jackfruit <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/jackfruit|title=Jackfruit |website=Merriam-Webster.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tamil==raanu\nGregory James, a professor with the language center of Hong Kong university believes that more than 100 words in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'' have Tamil origin, and there could be even more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-21/chennai/28371883_1_dictionaries-words-english-language |title=For this professor, tracking Tamil words in English is a passion|publisher=Times of India|date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> The third edition of the OED, published online since 2000, contains approximately 400,000 words.<ref>{{cite web|last=Simpson |first=John |date=2000 |title=Preface to the Third Edition of the OED |url=http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/preface-to-the-third-edition-of-the-oed/ |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Tamil word||Transliteration||Meaning in Tamil\n|-\n|[[Cash (currency)|Cash]]{{refn|group=notes|''Cash'' in the sense of \"small copper coins\" entered English from Tamil via Portuguese. ''Cash'' in the sense of \"ready money\" as opposed to invested wealth has a separate etymology, from Latin ''capsa'' via Middle French or Old Italian.}}||\u0b95\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bc1||k\u0101cu ||cash, money, coin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cash |title=cash<sup>2</sup> |publisher=Merriam-Webster.com |accessdate=2018-11-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Catamaran]]||\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd||kattumaram||tied wood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/catamaran|title=Catamaran; Define Catamaran at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cheroot]]||\u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1||suru\u1e6d\u1e6du||roll<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/cheroot|title=Cheroot; Define Cheroot at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Corundum]]||\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd/\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd||kuruntham/kuruvintham||ruby<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/corundum|title=Corundum; Define Corundum at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Culvert]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''culvert'' is unknown. Sources suggest it may come from an obscure technical term among canal diggers or a person's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/culvert |title=culvert|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=2018-06-15}}</ref>}}||\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1||kalvettu||carved/cut stone{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n|-\n|[[Mulligatawny]]||\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0bbf||milagu-ta\u1e47\u1e47\u012br/milagai-thanni||herb water<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=mulligatawny, ''n''. |encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |year=2003 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Patchouli]]||\u0baa\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc8 \u0b87\u0bb2\u0bc8||pachchai ilai||green leaf<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=patchouli+&searchmode=none |title=patchouli |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pandal]]||\u0baa\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd||pandhal||temporary shelter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/pandal|title=Pandal; Define Pandal at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> \n|}\n\n==Telugu==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Telugu word||Transliteration||Meaning in Telugu\n|-\n|[[Bandicoot]] || \u0c2a\u0c02\u0c26\u0c3f\u0c15\u0c4a\u0c15\u0c4d\u0c15\u0c41 || pandi-kokku || \"pig-rat\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=bandicoot |title=bandicoot |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pitta]] ||\u0c2a\u0c3f\u0c1f\u0c4d\u0c1f || pitta || young bird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/pitta |title=pitta |website=Oxford Dictionaries |accessdate=2016-04-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Kannada ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English word  \n!Kannada word\n!Transliteration\n!Meaning in Kannada\n|-\n|[[Bamboo]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''bamboo'' is uncertain. It is thought to have entered English from [[Malayo-Polynesian languages]], which borrowed it from Kannada.<ref name=\"bamboo\"/>}}\n|\u0cac\u0c82\u0cac\u0cc1\n|ba\u1e43bu\n|bamboo<ref name=\"bamboo\">{{Cite book|title=Illustrated Oxford Dictionary|last=Oxford University Press|first=1998|publisher=|year=|isbn=140532029-X|location=Great Britain|pages=}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dhole]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''dhole'' is unknown, but some sources suggest a connection to Kannada ''t\u014d\u1e37a'' (\u0ca4\u0ccb\u0cb3).<ref name=\"dhole\"/>}}\n|\u0ca4\u0ccb\u0cb3\n|t\u014d\u1e37a\n|wolf<ref name=\"dhole\">{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dhole |title=dhole |date=n.d. |website=Merriam-Webster.com |access-date=2016-04-08}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijra]] \n|\u0cb9\u0cbf\u0c9c\u0ca1\u0cbe\n|Hija\u1e0d\u0101\n|impotent man<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=hijra, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2009}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Indian English]]\n*[[List of English words of Indian origin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of English words of Indian origin]]\n[[Category:Lists of English words of foreign origin|Dravidian languages]]\n[[Category:Tamil language-related lists|English]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a list of [[English language|English]] words that are [[Loanword|borrowed]] directly or ultimately from [[Dravidian languages]]. Dravidian languages include [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Kannada language|Kannada]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], and a number of other languages spoken mainly in [[South Asia]]. The list is by no means exhaustive.\n\nSome of the words can be traced to specific languages, but others have disputed or uncertain origins. Words of disputed or less certain origin are in the \"Dravidian languages\" list. Where [[lexicographer]]s generally agree on a source language, the words are listed by language.\n\n==Dravidian languages==\n*[[wikt:aiyo|Aiyo]], a word used to express distress, regret and fear, either from Tamil ''aiy\u014d'' or [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] ayiy\u014d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/aiyo|title=aiyo|website=Oxford Dictionaries - English}}</ref>\n*[[Betel]], a leaf of a vine belonging to the family Piperaceae; from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''betel'', which probably comes from Tamil or Malayalam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=betel|title=Betel |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>\n*[[Candy]], crystallized sugar or confection made from sugar; via Persian ''qand'', which is probably from a Dravidian language, ultimately stemming from the Sanskrit root word 'Khanda'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=candy&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Candy |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n* [[Coir]], cord/rope, fibre from husk of coconut; from Malayalam ''kayar'' (\u0d15\u0d2f\u0d7c)<ref name=\"Coir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=coir|title=Coir |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> or Tamil ''kayiru'' (\u0b95\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0bc1).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/coir |title=Coir |publisher=Dictionary.com |accessdate=2015-07-26}}</ref> The origin of this word cannot be conclusively attributed to Malayalam or Tamil.\n*[[Congee]], porridge, water with rice; uncertain origin, possibly from Tamil ''kanji'' (\u0b95\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/congee |title=Congee |publisher=Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary |date=2012-08-31 |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref> Telugu or Kannada ''ga\u00f1ji'', or Malayalam ''ka\u1e47ni''<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=conjee, congee ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref>\n*[[Coolie]], a labourer or slave, a South Asian person; possibly from Tamil ''cooli'' (\u0b95\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bbf) \"labour\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/coolie|title=Coolie; Define Coolie at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> or possibly from ''Ko\u1e37\u012b'' \"[[Gujarati people]]\" in [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=coolie ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> which is not a Dravidian language\n*[[Bed frame|Cot]], a bedstead or a portable bed; via [[Hindi]] from [[Sanskrit]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=cot ''n.<sup>4</sup>''|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref> which in turn may have come from a Dravidian source such as Tamil ''kattil''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cot&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Cowry]], the shells of certain sea snails, or the snails themselves; via Hindi and [[Urdu]] from Sanskrit ''kaparda'' (\u0915\u092a\u0930\u094d\u0926),<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=cowry ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref> which may be related to Tamil ''kotu'' (\u0b95\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bc1) \"shell\"<ref name=\"etymonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cowrie&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Curry]], a variety of dishes flavored with a spicy sauce; [[cognate]]s exist in several Dravidian languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/curry|title=Curry; Define Curry at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n*[[Ginger]], a fragrant spice; exact route from Dravidian is uncertain, but possibly from Tamil ''inchi'' (\u0b87\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf) or Malayalam ''inchi'' (\u0d07\u0d1e\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d3f)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RSGOJB2lwmUC&pg|title=Origins of Plant Names-D.A. Patil}}</ref>\n* [[Godown]], synonym to warehouse; English from Malay, which in turn may have borrowed it from Telugu ''gi\u1e0dangi'' or Tamil ''ki\u1e6danku''<ref>{{Cite web|title=Define Godown at Dictionary.com|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/godown|accessdate=January 4, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Gunny sack|Gunny]], an inexpensive bag; from Sanskrit via Hindi and [[Marathi language|Marathi]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=gunny, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2000 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> perhaps ultimately from a Dravidian language such as [[Tulu language|Tulu]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n*[[Hot toddy]], beverage made of alcoholic liquor with hot water, sugar, and spices; from Hindi ''tari'' \"palm sap\", probably from a Dravidian language<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=toddy |title=toddy |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n*[[Jaggery]], coarse brown sugar made from palm and sugarcane; via Portuguese j\u00e1gara<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/jaggery|title=Jaggery|publisher=Merriam Webster Dictionary}}</ref> probably from Malayalam ''chakkara'' (\u0d1a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d30)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memidex.com/jaggery|title=Jaggery Etymology}}</ref> or Kannada ''sakkare'',  having its origins in Sanskrit.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=jaggery, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=second |year=1989 |isbn=9780198611868}}</ref>\n*[[Mango]], A tropical fruit;origin probably from Malayalam<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mango|title=Mango; Define Mango at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mango|title=Mango |website=Merriam-Webster.com}}</ref> or Tamil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=mango |title=mango (n.) |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>Achaya, K.T. (2003). The Story of Our Food. Universities Press. p. 7. {{ISBN|9788173712937}}.</ref>\n*[[Mongoose]], a small carnivorous mammal from southern Eurasia or Africa, known for killing snakes; probably ultimately from a Dravidian language, with spelling influenced by the English word ''goose''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=mongoose |title=mongoose |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n*[[Mung bean|Mung]], a type of bean; ultimately from Sanskrit ''mudga'' (\u092e\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0917), which is the name of the bean and the plant, perhaps via Tamil ''m\u016bngu'' (\u0bae\u0bc1\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1) \"soak\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mung+bean |title=Mung bean &#124; Define Mung bean at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> or perhaps from ''m\u0169g'' (\u092e\u0942\u0901\u0917), the name of the bean in Hindi,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=mung ''n.<sup>2</sup>''|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref> which is not a Dravidian language\n*[[Orange (word)|Orange]], a citrus fruit, or a color named for the fruit; cognates exist in several Dravidian languages<ref name=OED>{{cite encyclopedia | year = 2013 | title = orange ''n''.<sup>1</sup> and ''adj''.<sup>1</sup> | encyclopedia = Oxford English Dictionary online | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | url =http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/132163 |accessdate=2013-09-30}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n*[[Pagoda]], a religious building; etymology uncertain but perhaps influenced by Tamil ''pagavadi'' (\u0baa\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0b9f\u0bbf) \"house belonging to a deity\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=pagoda&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*Pariah, a social outcast; from Tamil ''pa\u1e5faiyar'' (\u0baa\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bb0\u0bcd) or Malayalam ''pa\u1e5fayan'', \"drummer\"<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=pariah, ''n''. and ''adj''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2008 |isbn=9780199571123}}</ref>\n*[[Peacock]], a type of bird; from [[Old English]] ''pawa'', the earlier etymology is uncertain, but one possible source is Tamil ''tokei'' (\u0ba4\u0bcb\u0b95\u0bc8) \"peacock feather\", via [[Latin]] or [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=peacock&allowed_in_frame=0 |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Sambal]], a spicy condiment; from [[Malay language|Malay]], which may have borrowed the word from a Dravidian language such as Tamil or Telugu<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/sambal|title=Sambal; Define Sambal at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n*[[Teak]], a tropical hardwood tree; called ''tekku'' (\u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1) in Tamil, ''tekka'' in Malayalam,  Telugu ''teku'', and Kannada ''tegu''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=teak |title=teak |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Malayalam==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Word||Transliteration||Meaning in Malayalam\n|-\n|[[Areca]]||\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15||adekka||areca nut <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/areca|title=Areca |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Catechu]]||\u0d15\u0d36\u0d42||cashoo||astringent made from acacia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/catechu|title=Catechu |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordreference.com/definition/catechu|title=Catechu |website=WordReference.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Copra]]||\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d30||kopra||copra: kernel of coconut <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=copra&searchmode=none |title=Copra |website=Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Calico]]||\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d34\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d||k\u0113\u0101\u1e3bikk\u0113\u0101\u1e6d||name of the place it originates from (Calicut) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/calico|title=Calico |website=Dictionary.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jackfruit]]||\u0d1a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15||Chakka||jackfruit <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/jackfruit|title=Jackfruit |website=Merriam-Webster.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tamil==\nGregory James, a professor with the language center of Hong Kong university believes that more than 100 words in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'' have Tamil origin, and there could be even more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-21/chennai/28371883_1_dictionaries-words-english-language |title=For this professor, tracking Tamil words in English is a passion|publisher=Times of India|date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> The third edition of the OED, published online since 2000, contains approximately 400,000 words.<ref>{{cite web|last=Simpson |first=John |date=2000 |title=Preface to the Third Edition of the OED |url=http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/preface-to-the-third-edition-of-the-oed/ |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Tamil word||Transliteration||Meaning in Tamil\n|-\n|[[Cash (currency)|Cash]]{{refn|group=notes|''Cash'' in the sense of \"small copper coins\" entered English from Tamil via Portuguese. ''Cash'' in the sense of \"ready money\" as opposed to invested wealth has a separate etymology, from Latin ''capsa'' via Middle French or Old Italian.}}||\u0b95\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bc1||k\u0101cu ||cash, money, coin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cash |title=cash<sup>2</sup> |publisher=Merriam-Webster.com |accessdate=2018-11-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Catamaran]]||\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd||kattumaram||tied wood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/catamaran|title=Catamaran; Define Catamaran at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cheroot]]||\u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1||suru\u1e6d\u1e6du||roll<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/cheroot|title=Cheroot; Define Cheroot at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Corundum]]||\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd/\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd||kuruntham/kuruvintham||ruby<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/corundum|title=Corundum; Define Corundum at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Culvert]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''culvert'' is unknown. Sources suggest it may come from an obscure technical term among canal diggers or a person's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/culvert |title=culvert|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=2018-06-15}}</ref>}}||\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1||kalvettu||carved/cut stone{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n|-\n|[[Mulligatawny]]||\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0bbf||milagu-ta\u1e47\u1e47\u012br/milagai-thanni||herb water<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=mulligatawny, ''n''. |encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |year=2003 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Patchouli]]||\u0baa\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc8 \u0b87\u0bb2\u0bc8||pachchai ilai||green leaf<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=patchouli+&searchmode=none |title=patchouli |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pandal]]||\u0baa\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd||pandhal||temporary shelter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/pandal|title=Pandal; Define Pandal at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref> \n|}\n\n==Telugu==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!English word||Telugu word||Transliteration||Meaning in Telugu\n|-\n|[[Bandicoot]] || \u0c2a\u0c02\u0c26\u0c3f\u0c15\u0c4a\u0c15\u0c4d\u0c15\u0c41 || pandi-kokku || \"pig-rat\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=bandicoot |title=bandicoot |publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=2014-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pitta]] ||\u0c2a\u0c3f\u0c1f\u0c4d\u0c1f || pitta || young bird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/pitta |title=pitta |website=Oxford Dictionaries |accessdate=2016-04-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Kannada ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English word  \n!Kannada word\n!Transliteration\n!Meaning in Kannada\n|-\n|[[Bamboo]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''bamboo'' is uncertain. It is thought to have entered English from [[Malayo-Polynesian languages]], which borrowed it from Kannada.<ref name=\"bamboo\"/>}}\n|\u0cac\u0c82\u0cac\u0cc1\n|ba\u1e43bu\n|bamboo<ref name=\"bamboo\">{{Cite book|title=Illustrated Oxford Dictionary|last=Oxford University Press|first=1998|publisher=|year=|isbn=140532029-X|location=Great Britain|pages=}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dhole]]{{refn|group=notes|The origin of ''dhole'' is unknown, but some sources suggest a connection to Kannada ''t\u014d\u1e37a'' (\u0ca4\u0ccb\u0cb3).<ref name=\"dhole\"/>}}\n|\u0ca4\u0ccb\u0cb3\n|t\u014d\u1e37a\n|wolf<ref name=\"dhole\">{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dhole |title=dhole |date=n.d. |website=Merriam-Webster.com |access-date=2016-04-08}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijra]] \n|\u0cb9\u0cbf\u0c9c\u0ca1\u0cbe\n|Hija\u1e0d\u0101\n|impotent man<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=hijra, ''n''.|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |year=2009}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Indian English]]\n*[[List of English words of Indian origin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of English words of Indian origin]]\n[[Category:Lists of English words of foreign origin|Dravidian languages]]\n[[Category:Tamil language-related lists|English]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4072:692:605f:5308:b96c:cbcd:78b6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Raanu)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_English_words_of_Dravidian_origin"}
{"title_page": "Renner Springs", "text_new": "{{nofootnotes|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox Australian place \n| type     = other\n| name     = Renner Springs\n| state    = NT\n| city =[[Pamayu, Northern Territory|Pamayu]]<ref name=\"placenames\"/>\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.31869|S|133.79573|E|type:city_region:AU-NT|display=title,inline}}\n| coord_ref = <ref name=\"placenames\">{{cite web |title=Place Names Register Extract for \"Renner Springs Roadhouse\" |url=https://www.ntlis.nt.gov.au/placenames/view.jsp?id=17985 |website=NT Place Names Register |publisher=Northern Territory Government |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| postcode = \n| est      = \n| pop      = \n| elevation= \n\n| dist1    = \n| dir1     = \n| location1= \n| dist2    = \n| dir2     = \n| location2= \n}}\n<!--  Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Renner_Springs.jpg|thumb|right| Renner Springs|{{puic|1=Image:Renner Springs.jpg|log=2008 March 10}}]] -->\n'''Renner Springs''' is a location in the [[Northern Territory]] of Australia. It is in the heart of the [[Barkly Tableland]]s cattle country. In fact, the town promotes itself as \"The Heart of the Beef Country.\" \n\nThe tiny settlement is on the [[Stuart Highway]], north of the intersection of the [[Barkly Highway]] and [[Tennant Creek]]. It is 662 kilometres from [[Alice Springs]], the largest town in the [[Outback]], and 820&nbsp;km from [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]].\n\nRenner Springs is usually regarded as the border between the tropical [[Top End]] and the temperate [[Red Centre]] regions. \n\n[[File:Renner Springs Windmill.jpg|thumb|Renner Springs Windmill at the Renner Springs Desert Inn]]\n\n\n\n==History==\nLike so many places along the Stuart Highway, it owes its origins to the [[Australian Overland Telegraph Line]]. It was named after [[Dr. Frederick Renner]], who was dispensing medical advice to the team working on the telegraph line when they passed through the springs in 1872. In 1877, Dr. Renner saw a flock of birds while working on the telegraph line and found that the birds were drawn to this particular area by the natural springs, which was later named Mud Springs. These freshwater springs, which bubble up from underground, helped the area surrounding Renner Springs achieve its importance because they provided water to the area. Lake Woods is just north of the town, near [[Elliott, Northern Territory|Elliott]] and [[Newcastle Waters, Northern Territory]].\n\n==Roadhouse==\nEstablished in the 1950s, the  Renner Springs Desert Hotel/Motel  also has gas, a bar and restaurant, game room and limited Internet access. A caravan park and shaded camp sites are also available. \n\nThe roadhouse building is an old army hut relocated after World War II from the army\u2019s staging camp 50&nbsp;km away at [[Banka Banka Station]], which dates from 1885.\n\n==Attractions==\n===Churchill's Head Rock===\nChurchill's Head Rock, considered one of Australia's most crass tourist attractions, is on the old Stuart Highway 78&nbsp;km south of Renner Springs. The rock, on the east of the old highway, looks vaguely like a profile of [[Winston Churchill]]. In order to make the image more persuasive, someone has stuck a piece of piping where the mouth should be so that the profile appears to be smoking a rather large cigar.\n\n===Attack Creek===\nAnother 11&nbsp;km south of Renner Springs is a monument marking the place where on 25 June 1860, [[John McDouall Stuart]], on his second attempt to cross Australia, was repulsed by hostile [[Indigenous Australians|Aborigines]]. It became appropriately known as Attack Creek.\n\n===Lubra's Lookout===\nA small plateau formation along the roadside where tribal women are said to watch the approach of tribes from a considerable distance. \n\n===Easter Rodeo===\nEach Easter, Renner Springs has a local rodeo and race meeting that attracts stockmen and punters from all over the Northern Territory. Being such a small community, the annual get-together, known as the Renner Springs Races, is actually held in Tennant Creek. \n\n==Temperatures==\nRenner Springs has high summer temperatures. The summer average maximum is about 35\u00b0C. The summer low is about 24\u00b0C.\n\nRenner Springs has warm winter temperatures. The winter high temperature is about 20\u00b0C. The winter low is about 5\u00b0C.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Northern-Territory/Renner-Springs/2005/02/17/1108500201661.html SMH Travel]\n*[http://www.totaltravel.com.au/travel/nt/redcentre/tennantcreek/guide/renner-springs Total Travel]\n*[http://www.australianexplorer.com/renner_springs.htm Australian Explorer]\n\n[[Category:Towns in the Northern Territory]]\n\n[[Category:Roadhouses in the Northern Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{nofootnotes|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox Australian place \n| type     = other\n| name     = Renner Springs\n| state    = NT\n| city =[[Pamayu, Northern Territory|Pamayu]]<ref name=\"placenames\"/>\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.31869|S|133.79573|E|type:city_region:AU-NT|display=title,inline}}\n| coord_ref = <ref name=\"placenames\">{{cite web |title=Place Names Register Extract for \"Renner Springs Roadhouse\" |url=https://www.ntlis.nt.gov.au/placenames/view.jsp?id=17985 |website=NT Place Names Register |publisher=Northern Territory Government |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| postcode = \n| est      = \n| pop      = \n| elevation= \n\n| dist1    = \n| dir1     = \n| location1= \n| dist2    = \n| dir2     = \n| location2= \n}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<!--  Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Renner_Springs.jpg|thumb|right| Renner Springs|{{puic|1=Image:Renner Springs.jpg|log=2008 March 10}}]] -->\n\n\n'''Renner Springs''' is a location in the [[Northern Territory]] of Australia. It is in the heart of the [[Barkly Tableland]]s cattle country. In fact, the town promotes itself as \"The Heart of the Beef Country.\" \n\nThe tiny settlement is on the [[Stuart Highway]], north of the intersection of the [[Barkly Highway]] and [[Tennant Creek]]. It is 662 kilometres from [[Alice Springs]], the largest town in the [[Outback]], and 820&nbsp;km from [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]].\n\nRenner Springs is usually regarded as the border between the tropical [[Top End]] and the temperate [[Red Centre]] regions. \n\n[[File:Renner Springs Windmill.jpg|thumb|Renner Springs Windmill at the Renner Springs Desert Inn]]\n\n\n\n==History==\nLike so many places along the Stuart Highway, it owes its origins to the [[Australian Overland Telegraph Line]]. It was named after [[Dr. Frederick Renner]], who was dispensing medical advice to the team working on the telegraph line when they passed through the springs in 1872. In 1877, Dr. Renner saw a flock of birds while working on the telegraph line and found that the birds were drawn to this particular area by the natural springs, which was later named Mud Springs. These freshwater springs, which bubble up from underground, helped the area surrounding Renner Springs achieve its importance because they provided water to the area. Lake Woods is just north of the town, near [[Elliott, Northern Territory|Elliott]] and [[Newcastle Waters, Northern Territory]].\n\n==Roadhouse==\nEstablished in the 1950s, the  Renner Springs Desert Hotel/Motel  also has gas, a bar and restaurant, game room and limited Internet access. A caravan park and shaded camp sites are also available. \n\nThe roadhouse building is an old army hut relocated after World War II from the army\u2019s staging camp 50&nbsp;km away at [[Banka Banka Station]], which dates from 1885.\n\n==Attractions==\n===Churchill's Head Rock===\nChurchill's Head Rock, considered one of Australia's most crass tourist attractions, is on the old Stuart Highway 78&nbsp;km south of Renner Springs. The rock, on the east of the old highway, looks vaguely like a profile of [[Winston Churchill]]. In order to make the image more persuasive, someone has stuck a piece of piping where the mouth should be so that the profile appears to be smoking a rather large cigar.\n\n===Attack Creek===\nAnother 11&nbsp;km south of Renner Springs is a monument marking the place where on 25 June 1860, [[John McDouall Stuart]], on his second attempt to cross Australia, was repulsed by hostile [[Indigenous Australians|Aborigines]]. It became appropriately known as Attack Creek.\n\n===Lubra's Lookout===\nA small plateau formation along the roadside where tribal women are said to watch the approach of tribes from a considerable distance. \n\n===Easter Rodeo===\nEach Easter, Renner Springs has a local rodeo and race meeting that attracts stockmen and punters from all over the Northern Territory. Being such a small community, the annual get-together, known as the Renner Springs Races, is actually held in Tennant Creek. \n\n==Temperatures==\nRenner Springs has high summer temperatures. The summer average maximum is about 35\u00b0C. The summer low is about 24\u00b0C.\n\nRenner Springs has warm winter temperatures. The winter high temperature is about 20\u00b0C. The winter low is about 5\u00b0C.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Northern-Territory/Renner-Springs/2005/02/17/1108500201661.html SMH Travel]\n*[http://www.totaltravel.com.au/travel/nt/redcentre/tennantcreek/guide/renner-springs Total Travel]\n*[http://www.australianexplorer.com/renner_springs.htm Australian Explorer]\n\n[[Category:Towns in the Northern Territory]]\n\n[[Category:Roadhouses in the Northern Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Cowdy001", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renner_Springs"}
{"title_page": "Greenhithe, New Zealand", "text_new": "{{For|the place in Kent, UK|Greenhithe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Greenhithe\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|46|S|174|41|E|display=it|region:NZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 8,421\n| popdate        = 2013\n| postcode       = 0632\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Schnapper Rock]]\n| northeast      = [[Unsworth Heights]]\n| east           = [[Bayview, New Zealand|Bayview]]\n| southeast      = [[Beach Haven, New Zealand|Beach Haven]]\n| south          = ([[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]])\n| southwest      = [[Hobsonville]]\n| west           = [[Herald Island, New Zealand|Herald Island]]\n| northwest      = [[Paremoremo]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n\n'''Greenhithe''' is a suburb of the [[North Shore City|North Shore]] of [[Auckland]] in New Zealand.\n\nIn 2001 Greenhithe had a population of 4,170, according to the census. It showed dramatic growth after the [[North Shore City Council]] determined that it was to be a major growth area. By 2013, the population had increased to 8,421.<ref name=Quickstats2013>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13265|Greenhithe}}</ref> Where once the typical section size was a quarter to half an acre, the newer subdivisions of Wainoni, Admiral's Court and others have reduced that to around 600m<sup>2</sup> (with a quarter acre being a shade over 1000m<sup>2</sup>). Since 1 November 2010, Greenhithe has been under the governance of [[Auckland Council]].\n\nGreenhithe includes the Wainoni area around Wainoni Park.<ref>{{cite book|title=Gregory's Auckland & Surrounds Street Directory|edition=3rd|isbn=978-0-7319-2048-8|year=2008|at=map 55}}</ref> Wainoni is part of the Greenhithe census area.<ref>{{cite map|url=http://archive.stats.govt.nz/StatsMaps/Home/Maps/2013-census-quickstats-about-a-place-map.aspx|title=2013 Census map|publisher=Stats New Zealand|at=Search->Area unit->Greenhithe}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, Greenhithe extended from the [[Upper Harbour Bridge]] through to Wainoni Park in the north. New subdivisions have extended the urban boundaries through to \"Greenhithe North\", including the northern part of Kyle Rd and Schnapper Rock. Until a proposed bridge is built to join the two Kyle Rds, these areas may have more community affiliation with [[Albany, New Zealand|Albany]].\n\nGreenhithe is bordered by Lucas Creek in the north and Hellyers Creek in the south. [[New Zealand Transport Agency]] completed the [[Upper Harbour Motorway]] through Greenhithe, in late 2007.\n\n==Education==\n\nGreenhithe School is a coeducational contributing primary (years 1-6) school with a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10 and a roll of 483.<ref>{{TKI|1299|Greenhithe School}}</ref> The school opened as a small rural school<ref name=School/> in 1893<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lutz |first1=Heike |last2=Chan |first2=Theresa |year=2011 |chapter=Albany and East Coast Bays |chapter-url= http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/SiteCollectionDocuments/aboutcouncil/localboards/devonporttakapunalocalboard/northshorethematicreviewvol2ch6end.pdf |chapter-format=PDF |title=North Shore Heritage: Thematic Review Report |volume=2 |page=409 |accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> and now has 520 to 600 students.<ref name=School>{{cite web |url= http://www.greenhithe.school.nz/ |title=Welcome |publisher=Greenhithe School |accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nUpper Harbour Primary School is a coeducational contributing primary school (years 1-6), with a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10 and a roll of 280.<ref>{{TKI|6955|Upper Harbour Primary School}}</ref> The school opened in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upperharbour.school.nz/|title=Welcome to Upper Harbour School|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.greenhithe.org.nz/ Greenhithe Residents Association]\n* [http://www.greenhithe.school.nz/ Greenhithe School]\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/collection/photos/search/searchterm/Greenhithe/field/title/ Photographs of Greenhithe] held in [[Auckland Libraries]]' heritage collections.\n\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Auckland Region]]\n[[Category:North Shore, New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the place in Kent, UK|Greenhithe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Greenhithe\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|46|S|174|41|E|display=it|region:NZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 8,421\n| popdate        = 2013\n| postcode       = 0632\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Schnapper Rock]]\n| northeast      = [[Unsworth Heights]]\n| east           = [[Bayview, New Zealand|Bayview]]\n| southeast      = [[Beach Haven, New Zealand|Beach Haven]]\n| south          = ([[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]])\n| southwest      = [[Hobsonville]]\n| west           = [[Herald Island, New Zealand|Herald Island]]\n| northwest      = [[Paremoremo]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n\n'''Greenhithe''' is a suburb of the [[North Shore City|North Shore]] of [[Auckland]] in New Zealand.\n\nIn 2001 Greenhithe had a population of 4,170, according to the census. It showed dramatic growth after the [[North Shore City Council]] determined that it was to be a major growth area. By 2013, the population had increased to 8,421.<ref name=Quickstats2013>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13265|Greenhithe}}</ref> Where once the typical section size was a quarter to half an acre, the newer subdivisions of Wainoni, Admiral's Court and others have reduced that to around 600m<sup>2</sup> (with a quarter acre being a shade over 1000m<sup>2</sup>). Since 1 November 2010, Greenhithe has been under the governance of [[Auckland Council]].\n\nGreenhithe includes the Wainoni area around Wainoni Park.<ref>{{cite book|title=Gregory's Auckland & Surrounds Street Directory|edition=3rd|isbn=978-0-7319-2048-8|year=2008|at=map 55}}</ref> Wainoni is part of the Greenhithe census area.<ref>{{cite map|url=http://archive.stats.govt.nz/StatsMaps/Home/Maps/2013-census-quickstats-about-a-place-map.aspx|title=2013 Census map|publisher=Stats New Zealand|at=Search->Area unit->Greenhithe}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, Greenhithe extended from the [[Upper Harbour Bridge]] through to Wainoni Park in the north. New subdivisions have extended the urban boundaries through to \"Greenhithe North\", including the northern part of Kyle Rd and Schnapper Rock. Until a proposed bridge is built to join the two Kyle Rds, these areas may have more community affiliation with [[Albany, New Zealand|Albany]].\n\nGreenhithe is bordered by Lucas Creek in the north and Hellyers Creek in the south. [[New Zealand Transport Agency]] completed the [[Upper Harbour Motorway]] through Greenhithe, in late 2007.\n\n==Education==\n\nGreenhithe School is a coeducational contributing primary (years 1-6) school with a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10 and a roll of 483.<ref>{{TKI|1299|Greenhithe School}}</ref> The school opened as a small rural school<ref name=School/> in 1893<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lutz |first1=Heike |last2=Chan |first2=Theresa |year=2011 |chapter=Albany and East Coast Bays |chapter-url= http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/SiteCollectionDocuments/aboutcouncil/localboards/devonporttakapunalocalboard/northshorethematicreviewvol2ch6end.pdf |chapter-format=PDF |title=North Shore Heritage: Thematic Review Report |volume=2 |page=409 |accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> and now has 520 to 600 students.<ref name=School>{{cite web |url= http://www.greenhithe.school.nz/ |title=Welcome |publisher=Greenhithe School |accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nUpper Harbour Primary School is a coeducational contributing primary school (years 1-6), with a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10 and a roll of 280.<ref>{{TKI|6955|Upper Harbour Primary School}}</ref> The school opened in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upperharbour.school.nz/|title=Welcome to Upper Harbour School|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.greenhithe.org.nz/ Greenhithe Residents Association]\n* [http://www.greenhithe.school.nz/ Greenhithe School]\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/?p=q&collection=p20062coll1&search=greenhithe&field=title&mode=all&conn= Photographs of Greenhithe] held in [[Auckland Libraries]]' heritage collections.\n\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Auckland Region]]\n[[Category:North Shore, New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Agh47", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated photographs link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenhithe,_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Kaymak", "text_new": "{{short description|creamy dairy product similar to clotted cream}}\n{{About|a creamy dairy product|the surname|Kaymak (surname)}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Kaymak\n| image            = Kaymak in Turkey.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Kaymak from [[Turkish cuisine|Turkey]]\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Turkic [[Central Asia]]\n| region           = [[Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey]], [[Greece]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Breakfast]] and [[dessert]]\n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]]\n| variations       = Kaymar, Gaymar, Qaimar, Qaimaq\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Kaymak''' is a creamy [[dairy product]] similar to [[clotted cream]], made from the [[milk]] of [[water buffalo]], [[cow]]s, [[sheep]], or [[goat]]s in [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asia]], some [[Balkan cuisine|Balkan]] countries, some [[Caucasus]] countries, [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] regions, [[Iranian cuisine|Iran]], [[Iraq]] and [[Afghan cuisine|Afghanistan]].\n\nThe traditional method of making kaymak is to boil the milk slowly, then simmer it for two hours over a very low heat. After the heat source is shut off, the cream is skimmed and left to chill (and mildly [[fermentation (food)|ferment]]) for several hours or days. Kaymak has a high percentage of [[milk fat]], typically about 60%. It has a thick, creamy consistency (not entirely compact, because of milk protein fibers) and a rich taste.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word kaymak has [[Central Asia]]n [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] origins, possibly formed from the verb kaymak, which means melt and molding of metal in [[Turkic languages|Turkic]].<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kaymak|title=kaymak|publisher=Ni\u015fanyanS\u00f6zl\u00fck|language=Turkish|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref> The first written records of the word kaymak is in the well-known book of [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], ''[[D\u012bw\u0101n Lugh\u0101t al-Turk]]''. The word remains as ''kaylgmak'' in Mongolian, and with small variations in Turkic languages as ''qaymaq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], ''qaymoq'' in [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], \u049b\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u049b in [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]] and [[Shor language|Shor]], \u043a\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u043a in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], ''kaymak'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]]<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\"/>, ga\u00fdmak in [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 (''kaimaghi'') in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], and \u03ba\u03b1\u03ca\u03bc\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 (''ka\u00efm\u00e1ki'') in [[Greek language|Greek]].\n\n==Turkey==\nShops in [[Turkey]] have been devoted to kaymak production and consumption for centuries. Kaymak is mainly consumed today for breakfast along with the traditional [[Turkish breakfast]]. One type of kaymak is found in the [[Afyonkarahisar]] region where the water buffalo are fed from the residue of poppy seeds pressed for oil. Kaymak can also describe the creamy foam in the traditional \"black\" Turkish coffee. Kaymak is traditionally eaten with [[baklava]] and other [[Turkish desserts]], fruit preserve and honey or as a filling in [[pancake]]s.\n\n==Balkans==\n[[File:Cicvara (10274863185).jpg|thumb|''Palenta'', cornmeal mush with kajmak and [[\u010dvarci]]]]\n[[File:Traditional wooden bowls for making kaymak.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Traditional wooden bowls for making and storing kaymak ([[Ethnographic Museum, Belgrade]])]]\nKnown as ''kajmak'', it is almost always made at home, though there is beginning to be commercial production. Kajmak is most expensive when freshest&mdash;only a day or two old. It can keep for weeks in the fridge but becomes harder and loses quality.<ref name=NIN>{{cite news |title=Sve srpske ka\u0161ike |first=Nikola|last=Vrzi\u0107 |url=http://www.nin.co.rs/2000-12/28/15928.html |work=[[NIN (magazine)|NIN]] |date=December 28, 2000 |accessdate=13 June 2012 |language=Serbian |format=Windows-1250}}</ref> Kajmak can also be matured in dried animal skin sacks; variation is called ''skorup''. ''Kajmak'' also describes the creamy foam in the Turkish coffee.\n\nIt is usually enjoyed as an [[appetizer]] or for Saturday morning breakfast, as Saturdays are market days with the best kajmak, but also as a [[condiment]]. The simplest recipe is ''lepinja sa kajmakom'' ([[bun]] [[bread]] filled with kaymak in Serbia) consumed for breakfast or as [[fast food]]. [[Bosnians]], [[Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]], and [[North Macedonia|Macedonians]] consider it a national meal. Other traditional dishes with kajmak (sold in restaurants) include ''[[pljeskavica]] sa kajmakom'' (the [[Balkans|Balkan]] version of a hamburger patty topped with melted kajmak), as well as ''ribi\u0107 u kajmaku'' (beef shank, simmered with kajmak).\n\n==Iraq==\n[[File:Iraqi-Gaimar-Kaymak.jpg|thumbnail|150px|Iraqi Gaimar made from [[water buffalo]] milk]]\nIn [[Iraq]], it is called gaimar, geymar or qaimar and is very popular. Iraqi gaimar is usually made from the rich, fatty milk of water buffaloes, which are prevalent in the marshes of Southern Iraq.\n\nIt is available both factory-produced and from local vendors (farmers) commonly known as Arab, Arbans or [[Madan (people)|Madan]], and so is sometimes referred to as ''gaimar Arab'', ''gaimar maadan'', or farmer's ''gaimar''.\n\nIraqis like to serve Gaimar for breakfast with fresh bread, honey or jam.  However, the most popular way is to spread it on a type of Iraqi pastry bread called \"Kahi\", smother it with [[date honey]] and then wash it down with hot tea.  Gaimar on kahi with date syrup is a long-standing traditional breakfast all over Baghdad and throughout the whole of Southern Iraq.\n\n==Iran==\nIn [[Iran]], ''sarsheer'' (\u0633\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u0631) is used to describe a different method which does not involve heating the milk, thus keeping enzymes and other cultures of the milk alive. The word ''kaymak'' (''qaymaq'') is also used for the boiled method. ''Qaymaq'' is a Turkish word used to describe this product among the Azari people of Iran.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''Qaimak'' or qaymaq has a thinner quality and is eaten for breakfast meals usually with bread. People typically top qaimak with honey, sugar, or mix it with jam. It can be spread on pastries or even added to milk tea. Qaimak can be purchased at grocery stores in Afghanistan or made at home. It is quite a long process to make at home, involving hours of stirring the milk pot. Qaimak can be found at Afghan/Iranian grocery stores in the west, packaged qaimak is not as rich as homemade. While a lot qaimak variations are made from buffalo milk, Afghan qaimak can be made from cows' milk.\n\n==Georgia==\n[[File:Kaimaghi.jpg|thumb|A bucket containing kaimaghi in a home in Keda, Georgia.]]\nIn the [[Adjara]] region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], bordering Turkey, \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 or ''kaimaghi'' is made from cow milk in homes in the mountainous municipalities of [[Keda, Georgia|Keda]], [[Shuakhevi]], and [[Khulo]]. It is typically eaten with [[Georgian cheese]] and/or bread, and is only rarely served in restaurants.\n\n==Greece==\n''Kaimaki'' in [[Greece]] refers to mastic-flavored ice cream that is widely available and often served alongside traditional desserts.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Malai]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928145321/http://editore.slowfood.com/editore/riviste/slowark/EN/25/papavero.html The Poppy Growers of \u0130smailk\u00f6y (2002)]\n* Davidson, Alan. Oxford Companion to Food (1999). \"Kaymak\", pp.&nbsp;428\u2013429. {{ISBN|0-19-211579-0}}\n* [http://www.travelserbia.info/serbian-cuisine.php An Introduction into the Serbian Cuisine]\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624222707/http://www.havuzsauna.com/detay.asp?y=639 The famous kaymak breakfast of \"Pando Usta\" at Be\u015fikta\u015f, Istanbul]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060926222537/http://faq.macedonia.org/cuisine/kajmak.html Kaymak recipe]\n\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Cuisine of Serbia}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{List of intangible cultural heritage of Serbia}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Appetizers]]\n[[Category:Balkan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Condiments]]\n[[Category:Fermented dairy products]]\n[[Category:Iranian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Kyrgyz cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|creamy dairy product similar to clotted cream}}\n{{About|a creamy dairy product|the surname|Kaymak (surname)}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Kaymak\n| image            = Kaymak in Turkey.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Kaymak from [[Turkish cuisine|Turkey]]\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Turkic [[Central Asia]]\n| region           = [[Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey]], [[Greece]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Breakfast]] and [[dessert]]\n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]]\n| variations       = Kaymar, Gaymar, Qaimar, Qaimaq\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Kaymak''' is a creamy [[dairy product]] similar to [[clotted cream]], made from the [[milk]] of [[water buffalo]], [[cow]]s, [[sheep]], or [[goat]]s in [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asia]], some [[Balkan cuisine|Balkan]] countries, some [[Caucasus]] countries, [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] regions, [[Iranian cuisine|Iran]], [[Iraq]] and [[Afghan cuisine|Afghanistan]].\n\nThe traditional method of making kaymak is to boil the milk slowly, then simmer it for two hours over a very low heat. After the heat source is shut off, the cream is skimmed and left to chill (and mildly [[fermentation (food)|ferment]]) for several hours or days. Kaymak has a high percentage of [[milk fat]], typically about 60%. It has a thick, creamy consistency (not entirely compact, because of milk protein fibers) and a rich taste.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word kaymak has [[Central Asia]]n [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] origins, possibly formed from the verb kaymak, which means melt and molding of metal in [[Turkic languages|Turkic]].<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kaymak|title=kaymak|publisher=Ni\u015fanyanS\u00f6zl\u00fck|language=Turkish|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref> The first written records of the word kaymak is in the well-known book of [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], ''[[D\u012bw\u0101n Lugh\u0101t al-Turk]]''. The word remains as ''kaylgmak'' in Mongolian, and with small variations in Turkic languages as ''qaymaq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], ''qaymoq'' in [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], \u049b\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u049b in [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]] and [[Shor language|Shor]], \u043a\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u043a in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], ''kaymak'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]]<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\"/>, ga\u00fdmak in [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 (''kaimaghi'') in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], and \u03ba\u03b1\u03ca\u03bc\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 (''ka\u00efm\u00e1ki'') in [[Greek language|Greek]].\n\n==Turkey==\nShops in [[Turkey]] have been devoted to kaymak production and consumption for centuries. Kaymak is mainly consumed today for breakfast along with the traditional [[Turkish breakfast]]. One type of kaymak is found in the [[Afyonkarahisar]] region where the water buffalo are fed from the residue of poppy seeds pressed for oil. Kaymak can also describe the creamy foam in the traditional \"black\" Turkish coffee. Kaymak is traditionally eaten with [[baklava]] and other [[Turkish desserts]], fruit preserve and honey or as a filling in [[pancake]]s.\n\n==Balkans==\n[[File:Cicvara (10274863185).jpg|thumb|''Palenta'', cornmeal mush with kajmak and [[\u010dvarci]]]]\n[[File:Traditional wooden bowls for making kaymak.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Traditional wooden bowls for making and storing kaymak ([[Ethnographic Museum, Belgrade]])]]\nKnown as ''kajmak'', it is almost always made at home, though there is beginning to be commercial production. Kajmak is most expensive when freshest&mdash;only a day or two old. It can keep for weeks in the fridge but becomes harder and loses quality.<ref name=NIN>{{cite news |title=Sve srpske ka\u0161ike |first=Nikola|last=Vrzi\u0107 |url=http://www.nin.co.rs/2000-12/28/15928.html |work=[[NIN (magazine)|NIN]] |date=December 28, 2000 |accessdate=13 June 2012 |language=Serbian |format=Windows-1250}}</ref> Kajmak can also be matured in dried animal skin sacks; variation is called ''skorup''. ''Kajmak'' also describes the creamy foam in the Turkish coffee.\n\nIt is usually enjoyed as an [[appetizer]] or for Saturday morning breakfast, as Saturdays are market days with the best kajmak, but also as a [[condiment]]. The simplest recipe is ''lepinja sa kajmakom'' ([[bun]] [[bread]] filled with kaymak in Serbia) consumed for breakfast or as [[fast food]]. [[Bosnians]], [[Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]], and [[North Macedonia|Macedonians]] consider it a national meal. Other traditional dishes with kajmak (sold in restaurants) include ''[[pljeskavica]] sa kajmakom'' (the [[Balkans|Balkan]] version of a hamburger patty topped with melted kajmak), as well as ''ribi\u0107 u kajmaku'' (beef shank, simmered with kajmak).\n\n==Iraq==\n[[File:Iraqi-Gaimar-Kaymak.jpg|thumbnail|150px|Iraqi Gaimar made from [[water buffalo]] milk]]\nIn [[Iraq]], it is called gaimar, geymar or qaimar and is very popular. Iraqi gaimar is usually made from the rich, fatty milk of water buffaloes which are prevalent in the marshes of Southern Iraq. \nIt is available both factory produced and from local vendors (farmers) commonly known as Arab, Arbans or [[Madan (people)|Madan]], thus the product is sometimes referred to as ''gaimar Arab'', ''gaimar maadan'', or farmer's ''gaimar''. \n\nIraqis like to serve Gaimar for breakfast with fresh bread, honey or jam.  However the most popular way is to spread it on a type of Iraqi pastry bread called \"Kahi\", smother it with [[date honey]] and then wash it down with hot tea.  Gaimar on kahi with date syrup is a long-standing traditional breakfast all over Baghdad and throughout the whole of Southern Iraq.\n\n==Iran==\nIn [[Iran]], ''sarsheer'' (\u0633\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u0631) is used to describe a different method which does not involve heating the milk, thus keeping enzymes and other cultures of the milk alive. The word ''kaymak'' (''qaymaq'') is also used for the boiled method. ''Qaymaq'' is a Turkish word used to describe this product among the Azari people of Iran.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''Qaimak'' or qaymaq has a thinner quality and is eaten for breakfast meals usually with bread. People typically top qaimak with honey, sugar, or mix it with jam. It can be spread on pastries or even added to milk tea. Qaimak can be purchased at grocery stores in Afghanistan or made at home. It is quite a long process to make at home, involving hours of stirring the milk pot. Qaimak can be found at Afghan/Iranian grocery stores in the west, packaged qaimak is not as rich as homemade. While a lot qaimak variations are made from buffalo milk, Afghan qaimak can be made from cows' milk.\n\n==Georgia==\n[[File:Kaimaghi.jpg|thumb|A bucket containing kaimaghi in a home in Keda, Georgia.]]\nIn the [[Adjara]] region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], bordering Turkey, \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 or ''kaimaghi'' is made from cow milk in homes in the mountainous municipalities of [[Keda, Georgia|Keda]], [[Shuakhevi]], and [[Khulo]]. It is typically eaten with [[Georgian cheese]] and/or bread, and is only rarely served in restaurants.\n\n==Greece==\n''Kaimaki'' in [[Greece]] refers to mastic-flavored ice cream that is widely available and often served alongside traditional desserts.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Malai]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928145321/http://editore.slowfood.com/editore/riviste/slowark/EN/25/papavero.html The Poppy Growers of \u0130smailk\u00f6y (2002)]\n* Davidson, Alan. Oxford Companion to Food (1999). \"Kaymak\", pp.&nbsp;428\u2013429. {{ISBN|0-19-211579-0}}\n* [http://www.travelserbia.info/serbian-cuisine.php An Introduction into the Serbian Cuisine]\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624222707/http://www.havuzsauna.com/detay.asp?y=639 The famous kaymak breakfast of \"Pando Usta\" at Be\u015fikta\u015f, Istanbul]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060926222537/http://faq.macedonia.org/cuisine/kajmak.html Kaymak recipe]\n\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Cuisine of Serbia}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{List of intangible cultural heritage of Serbia}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Appetizers]]\n[[Category:Balkan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Condiments]]\n[[Category:Fermented dairy products]]\n[[Category:Iranian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Kyrgyz cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "Mucketymuck", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIraq", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaymak"}
{"title_page": "Morelos", "text_new": "{{short description|State of Mexico}}\n{{About|the Mexican state|the Mexican Independence War leader|Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos|the city named after him|Morelia}}\n{{Other uses|Morelos (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Morelos\n| official_name           = ''Estado soleado y Soberano de Morelos''\n| native_name_lang        = Cuauh\u00e1huac [[Nahua]]\n| settlement_type         = [[States of Mexico|State]]\n| image_flag              = Flag of Morelos.svg\n| flag_size               = 160px\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_coat_of_arms      = Coat of arms of Morelos.svg\n| coat_of_arms_size       = 80px\n| nickname                = <!--NO-->\n| motto                   = ''Tierra y Libertad''{{Clear}}<small>''(Land and Liberty)''</small> (Coat of arms: \"La tierra es de quien la trabaja con sus manos [The land belongs to those who work it with their hands]\"\n| anthem                  = Marcha Morelense\n| image_map               = Morelos in Mexico (zoom).svg\n| map_caption             = State of Morelos within Mexico\n| coordinates             = {{coord|18|45|N|99|4|W|region:MX-MOR_type:adm1st|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Mexico]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Capital city|Capital]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Cuernavaca]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of cities in Mexico|Largest&nbsp;City]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Cuernavaca]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Municipalities of Mexico|Municipalities]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Municipalities of Morelos|33]]\n| established_title       = [[Sovereign state|Admission]]\n| established_date        = April 17, 1869<ref>{{cite news|title=Se crea el Estado de Morelos|url=http://www.memoriapoliticademexico.org/Efemerides/4/17041869.html|accessdate=February 4, 2019|language=Spanish|trans-title=Creation of th